{
  "doc_id": "10978",
  "text": "Marine seaweeds are colonized by diverse microbial communities [CITATION_1] (Lachnit et al., , 2011 [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , which interact with their hosts in both positive and negative ways [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . As with other eukaryotes, seaweeds and microorganisms can be considered a \"holobiont, \" an intimately interacting association of microorganisms and their host [CITATION_8] . The relationship between the host and its microbiome can be fundamental to the functioning of the host, and when disturbed can result in disease [CITATION_9] . This is particularly relevant to marine systems, where diseases can impact whole populations [e.g., seagrass wasting disease [CITATION_10] , coral or algal bleaching [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] or sea star wasting disease [CITATION_13] ], and for which there is evidence for an increasing frequency or intensity of diseases [CITATION_14] . This later observation may be due to increased environmental stress, such as temperature or eutrophication, which are potentially important factors that destabilize the holobiont and make it more susceptible to pathogen infection [CITATION_15] . Knowing all the association partners is the first step to understanding the health and functional outcomes for marine holobionts, and to the potential consequences of disease in these systems.",
